You need a graphing calculator to solve quadratic equations and obtain their roots. Casio calculators are user-friendly, Texas calculators are not. Here, I will show how to get the roots first using a Casio calculator and then using a Texas calculator.
You need to follow the following steps to solve a quadratic formula in a Casio fx 9750GII:
\begin{solutionbox} \begin{enumerate}[label=\protect\circled{\color{white}\arabic*}]
\item \begin{bf}Step one:\end{bf}   Press \keystroke{\large Menu} and 8.
 \item \begin{bf}Step two:\end{bf} Press the Poly (F2) menu.\ and select the degree: 2. Now enter the a, b, and c coefficients of the polynomial.
\item \begin{bf}Step three:\end{bf} At this point, you will have the two roots
\end{enumerate}
\end{solutionbox} 
You need to follow the following steps to solve a quadratic formula in a Texas TI 84:
\begin{solutionbox} \begin{enumerate}[label=\protect\circled{\color{white}\arabic*}]
\item \begin{bf}Step one:\end{bf} To open a new program: press \keystroke{\large PRGM}, select New and type QUAD, the program name, using letter keys. Now, press \keystroke{\large ENTER}
 \item \begin{bf}Step two:\end{bf} press \keystroke{\large PRGM}, I/O, Prompt, press \keystroke{\large ENTER}, type: \keystroke{\large ALPHA}+A, then press the comma key, \keystroke{\large ALPHA}+B and comma, \keystroke{\large ALPHA}+C, press \keystroke{\large ENTER}
 \item \begin{bf}Step three:\end{bf} Write the following equations using Alpha/Numeric keys: 
 \begin{center}(-B+\keystroke{\large $\sqrt{}$}(B$^2$ -4AC))/(2A)\end{center} Now press \keystroke{\large STO} X and \keystroke{\large ENTER} 
\item \begin{bf}Step four:\end{bf} Write the following equations using Alpha/Numeric keys: 
\begin{center}(-B-\keystroke{\large $\sqrt{}$}(B$^2$ -4AC))/(2A)\end{center}
Now press \keystroke{\large STO} Y and \keystroke{\large ENTER}
\item \begin{bf}Step five:\end{bf} Press \keystroke{\large PRGM}, I/O, Disp, type: "ROOTS EQUAL" (with quotes), press \keystroke{\large ,}, \keystroke{\large ALPHA}+X, press \keystroke{\large ,} and now, \keystroke{\large ALPHA}+Y, press \keystroke{\large ENTER}
\item \begin{bf}Step six:\end{bf} Press \keystroke{\large 2nd} and \keystroke{\large MODE} to quit and save. 
\item \begin{bf}Step seven:\end{bf} Press \keystroke{\large PRGM} key, select QUAD, press \keystroke{\large ENTER} twice to start program. It will then ask for A=?, B=?, and C=? Enter values for A, B, and C pressing \keystroke{\large ENTER} after each value it will then display the two roots if they are real.


\end{enumerate}
\end{solutionbox} 